1
00:00:00,300 --> 00:00:02,134
<i>Previously on Mad Men...</i>

2
00:00:02,350 --> 00:00:04,609
He is not your friend,
he is the enemy.

3
00:00:05,495 --> 00:00:07,337
You let Don talk,
you should know better.

4
00:00:07,433 --> 00:00:08,849
The guy's not a salesman.

5
00:00:08,952 --> 00:00:11,332
- Why do we care what that guy wants?
- Because he's a client.

6
00:00:11,972 --> 00:00:13,365
I don't want to live on
the Upper East side.

7
00:00:13,463 --> 00:00:16,603
I saw us raising our kids in a place
with more different kinds of people.

8
00:00:18,306 --> 00:00:19,541
I don't know what to say.

9
00:00:19,649 --> 00:00:23,361
Say you're gonna be the first American
to complete a successful heart transplant.

10
00:00:23,770 --> 00:00:26,183
I could come up and
stay there tonight, if you want.

11
00:00:27,421 --> 00:00:28,764
We'll be fine.

12
00:00:55,826 --> 00:00:58,481
Sync and corrections by n17t01
www.addic7ed.com

13
00:01:12,372 --> 00:01:14,706
Are you sure you don't want
me to order in some food?

14
00:01:14,740 --> 00:01:17,709
- Chinese?
- I'm sorry this is taking so long.

15
00:01:17,743 --> 00:01:21,212
It's a common mistake
to not ask questions

16
00:01:21,246 --> 00:01:23,682
when you want something because
you're afraid of the answers.

17
00:01:23,716 --> 00:01:25,784
So you want something?

18
00:01:25,818 --> 00:01:27,385
I'm interested.

19
00:01:27,419 --> 00:01:31,288
And considering the precedent
for small agencies,

20
00:01:31,322 --> 00:01:33,724
this is how we might
take you public.

21
00:01:33,758 --> 00:01:37,227
With one and a half
million shares outstanding

22
00:01:37,261 --> 00:01:40,831
before the offering, we'd sell
400,000 additional shares

23
00:01:40,865 --> 00:01:42,967
to the public at $9 a share.

24
00:01:43,001 --> 00:01:45,903
- 12 a share.
- It's not an insult.

25
00:01:45,937 --> 00:01:48,771
Our valuation of your company was
made after careful analysis.

26
00:01:48,806 --> 00:01:50,539
Of papers you spent
20 minutes with?

27
00:01:50,574 --> 00:01:52,909
I can't take this
to the rest of my partners,

28
00:01:52,943 --> 00:01:55,444
but I can take it
to other underwriters.

29
00:01:56,780 --> 00:01:59,749
I'll need these documents
for 24 hours.

30
00:02:06,889 --> 00:02:09,658
These papers are spotless.
My compliments to the chef.

31
00:02:12,128 --> 00:02:13,662
Shall we?

32
00:02:23,171 --> 00:02:25,940
You don't think Cooper pushed that
poor banker too hard, do you?

33
00:02:25,974 --> 00:02:27,441
We don't want to lose him.

34
00:02:27,475 --> 00:02:29,543
Certainly not.

35
00:02:31,713 --> 00:02:33,480
It's a marvel.

36
00:02:33,515 --> 00:02:35,381
Everyone wants you, don't they?

37
00:02:35,415 --> 00:02:37,083
Pete, no.

38
00:02:39,053 --> 00:02:42,488
No, I believe our primary
hurdle has been cleared.

39
00:02:42,523 --> 00:02:44,257
And our secondary one?

40
00:02:44,291 --> 00:02:46,926
Don't worry about Don.
Even at nine a share,

41
00:02:46,961 --> 00:02:50,229
your part of the company alone
will be worth nearly $1 million.

42
00:02:53,232 --> 00:02:55,333
My goodness.

43
00:02:57,470 --> 00:02:59,171
You're flushed.

44
00:03:00,173 --> 00:03:02,641
I drank too fast.

45
00:03:02,676 --> 00:03:04,743
I don't think Don
cares about money.

46
00:03:04,778 --> 00:03:07,011
That may be true.
God bless him.

47
00:03:07,079 --> 00:03:09,280
But he's tired of playing
in the bush leagues.

48
00:03:09,314 --> 00:03:11,683
This capitalization
will double our size

49
00:03:11,684 --> 00:03:13,504
and that will turn his head.

50
00:03:15,688 --> 00:03:17,188
You want another?

51
00:03:17,222 --> 00:03:20,324
No. I can hardly walk
and you know it.

52
00:03:22,494 --> 00:03:24,995
I hope Clara reminded you
tomorrow's Mother's Day.

53
00:03:26,179 --> 00:03:27,783
Thank you, I'm aware.

54
00:03:38,215 --> 00:03:39,208
Ow.

55
00:03:39,242 --> 00:03:40,976
Just wanted to make sure
you were still here.

56
00:03:41,011 --> 00:03:43,179
I am, but not for long.

57
00:03:43,213 --> 00:03:45,280
You don't even know
what time it is.

58
00:03:46,817 --> 00:03:48,350
I do.

59
00:03:48,384 --> 00:03:51,220
Because I already got up
and put on my face.

60
00:03:51,254 --> 00:03:53,488
Is that what you do?

61
00:03:53,523 --> 00:03:56,091
- I wondered.
- I have to go.

62
00:03:58,227 --> 00:04:00,428
Daisy, you're a tease.

63
00:04:00,462 --> 00:04:03,331
What more could I give you?

64
00:04:03,365 --> 00:04:06,601
Look, the first-class lounge would
be a darker place without you,

65
00:04:06,635 --> 00:04:08,770
but you're supposed to have
your ear to the ground.

66
00:04:08,804 --> 00:04:12,206
I feel like you only call me
when you want to see me.

67
00:04:12,240 --> 00:04:14,775
Am I going to see you tomorrow?

68
00:04:14,809 --> 00:04:18,678
If there's a flight filled with P&G
executives headed back to Cincinnati.

69
00:04:18,713 --> 00:04:21,782
- How about tonight?
- I have plans.

70
00:04:21,816 --> 00:04:25,119
Some other boyfriend? The one
you give all the leads to?

71
00:04:28,789 --> 00:04:30,589
With my mother.

72
00:04:30,624 --> 00:04:32,024
It's Mother's Day.

73
00:04:32,059 --> 00:04:34,227
Don't go.

74
00:04:34,261 --> 00:04:37,163
I have to.

75
00:04:37,197 --> 00:04:39,031
But my mother just died.

76
00:05:10,729 --> 00:05:12,797
What are you doing?

77
00:05:14,466 --> 00:05:16,966
You told me you wanted
me here Sunday morning.

78
00:05:17,001 --> 00:05:18,769
I'm here.

79
00:05:20,305 --> 00:05:22,639
Peter, don't.

80
00:05:25,209 --> 00:05:28,244
So we'll just maintain every
other aspect of this marriage

81
00:05:28,279 --> 00:05:30,280
except the one that matters.

82
00:05:30,315 --> 00:05:32,247
You mean Tammy?

83
00:05:32,282 --> 00:05:35,384
Will you stop holding
the axe over my neck?

84
00:05:35,419 --> 00:05:39,188
So you'd rather I divorce you just
so you know where things stand?

85
00:05:39,222 --> 00:05:42,124
You don't care that I want you.

86
00:05:42,158 --> 00:05:44,993
I've taken note
of your efforts.

87
00:05:45,028 --> 00:05:46,929
I'm going to get her.

88
00:05:48,731 --> 00:05:50,865
Well...

89
00:05:50,899 --> 00:05:53,067
you're gonna be sorry
when this is over.

90
00:05:53,101 --> 00:05:55,370
You've given up on me
at exactly the wrong time.

91
00:05:55,404 --> 00:05:57,505
I have big things coming.

92
00:05:57,540 --> 00:05:59,708
You have no idea.

93
00:05:59,742 --> 00:06:01,676
Well, I'll take note
of that, too.

94
00:06:06,247 --> 00:06:07,946
_

95
00:06:07,981 --> 00:06:09,666
_

96
00:06:09,809 --> 00:06:10,743
_

97
00:06:10,851 --> 00:06:13,383
_

98
00:06:13,484 --> 00:06:14,823
_

99
00:06:14,928 --> 00:06:17,123
_

100
00:06:17,383 --> 00:06:18,948
_

101
00:06:21,962 --> 00:06:23,963
Could you get that?

102
00:06:28,969 --> 00:06:31,103
- Arnold. Come in.
- Hi.

103
00:06:31,137 --> 00:06:33,339
I'm sorry to bother you.
Do you have any wrapping paper?

104
00:06:33,374 --> 00:06:35,640
It's an emergency.

105
00:06:35,675 --> 00:06:37,809
Good morning.

106
00:06:37,844 --> 00:06:40,579
Sorry, this is
Megan's mother Marie.

107
00:06:40,613 --> 00:06:43,715
We passed in the lobby.
I thought you were Megan.

108
00:06:43,750 --> 00:06:46,251
Dr. Arnold Rosen
at your service.

109
00:06:46,285 --> 00:06:48,653
- Enchanté.
- <i>Are you French?</i>

110
00:06:48,688 --> 00:06:51,289
My kid's going to Paris.
Should I keep him home?

111
00:06:51,323 --> 00:06:54,124
I am French,
but I live in Montreal.

112
00:06:54,158 --> 00:06:56,260
And, yes, I believe so.

113
00:06:56,294 --> 00:06:58,128
I assume this isn't
a medical emergency.

114
00:06:58,162 --> 00:07:00,197
Mitchell--
that's my son--

115
00:07:00,231 --> 00:07:02,400
he came home and surprised
her for Mother's Day.

116
00:07:02,434 --> 00:07:05,102
- How long is he staying?
- Who knows?

117
00:07:05,136 --> 00:07:07,670
I know he thinks a morning stroll
in Central Park is a gift,

118
00:07:07,705 --> 00:07:11,173
but Sylvia's gonna
expect an actual gift.

119
00:07:11,208 --> 00:07:14,444
Do you want my flowers?
I'm quite done with them.

120
00:07:14,478 --> 00:07:16,813
Thank you, Mother.

121
00:07:16,847 --> 00:07:19,749
You're a lifesaver.

122
00:07:24,020 --> 00:07:26,722
He's a surgeon. He's working
on heart transplants.

123
00:07:26,756 --> 00:07:30,426
Wealthy, talented,
handsome--

124
00:07:30,460 --> 00:07:32,628
I would not leave them alone.

125
00:07:32,662 --> 00:07:34,963
I'm more worried about you.

126
00:07:37,934 --> 00:07:39,867
There's poop
on the stairs again.

127
00:07:39,902 --> 00:07:42,470
Somebody's dog got in.

128
00:07:42,504 --> 00:07:44,439
No, it's human.

129
00:07:44,473 --> 00:07:46,607
I think it's from the tenant.

130
00:07:46,642 --> 00:07:48,275
She wouldn't do that.

131
00:07:48,310 --> 00:07:49,844
She's a junkie.
She doesn't care.

132
00:07:49,878 --> 00:07:51,846
I want her out.

133
00:07:51,880 --> 00:07:53,881
We can't do that.

134
00:07:57,384 --> 00:07:59,018
How is your mother?

135
00:08:00,287 --> 00:08:02,756
I got curtains.
She wants to come visit.

136
00:08:02,790 --> 00:08:05,425
Ah!
Ow! Ow.

137
00:08:05,460 --> 00:08:07,126
Jesus.

138
00:08:07,161 --> 00:08:08,695
We have to hire a handyman.

139
00:08:08,729 --> 00:08:10,831
Why?
It's a waste of money.

140
00:08:10,865 --> 00:08:12,998
Because you have no idea
what you're doing.

141
00:08:29,815 --> 00:08:32,851
Herb Rennet called. He's
canceling dinner tonight.

142
00:08:32,885 --> 00:08:34,652
That's a relief.

143
00:08:34,687 --> 00:08:36,120
We can still have dinner.

144
00:08:36,154 --> 00:08:37,589
I'd love to discuss
some things with you.

145
00:08:37,623 --> 00:08:39,757
Let's enjoy our reprieve.

146
00:08:39,792 --> 00:08:41,493
Of course.

147
00:08:42,928 --> 00:08:45,963
Psst.
Close the door.

148
00:08:48,366 --> 00:08:50,701
Did he say your dinner
with Jaguar is off?

149
00:08:50,735 --> 00:08:53,937
Yes, unless it was the
world's most boring dream.

150
00:08:53,972 --> 00:08:56,206
Well, it's on,
but Pete's not invited.

151
00:08:56,240 --> 00:08:59,075
Herb Rennet wants a word alone
to straighten things out.

152
00:08:59,110 --> 00:09:00,610
Why can't you handle it?

153
00:09:00,644 --> 00:09:03,078
This could be fatal.
You're going.

154
00:09:03,113 --> 00:09:06,148
And my plan is to pack it with
spouses to limit the explosion.

155
00:09:06,182 --> 00:09:07,683
Megan made plans
with her mother.

156
00:09:07,718 --> 00:09:09,018
She thought I had
a business dinner.

157
00:09:09,052 --> 00:09:11,453
Marie's in town?
Fantastic.

158
00:09:11,488 --> 00:09:14,023
Bring her along.
That's perfect.

159
00:09:14,057 --> 00:09:15,857
Tell her I insisted.

160
00:09:18,060 --> 00:09:20,361
In attendance
I have Jim Cutler,

161
00:09:20,396 --> 00:09:22,363
Frank Gleason, and Ted Chaough.

162
00:09:22,398 --> 00:09:24,733
Sweetheart, this is a creative meeting.
What are you doing?

163
00:09:24,767 --> 00:09:27,268
It's for the purposes
of the memorandum.

164
00:09:27,302 --> 00:09:30,805
Well, Ted, some men love
women, some love memos.

165
00:09:30,840 --> 00:09:33,306
I want to go over where we are
on Chevrolet again

166
00:09:33,341 --> 00:09:35,308
and devote our final days
to overdoing it

167
00:09:35,343 --> 00:09:37,144
on the artwork for
the top three campaigns.

168
00:09:37,178 --> 00:09:39,246
I cannot look at these again.

169
00:09:39,280 --> 00:09:41,415
I told you, they're very keen
on the rocket ship thing

170
00:09:41,449 --> 00:09:42,917
with the astronaut anecdotes.

171
00:09:42,951 --> 00:09:44,785
You told them
about the astronauts?

172
00:09:44,819 --> 00:09:47,387
I had to.
It was too vague otherwise.

173
00:09:47,422 --> 00:09:48,821
I don't want to draw
any more rockets

174
00:09:48,856 --> 00:09:50,289
and I don't want to stare
at this work again.

175
00:09:50,323 --> 00:09:53,059
We should have never
resigned Alfa Romeo.

176
00:09:53,093 --> 00:09:55,494
What, is this mystery Chevy
gonna be in "The Graduate"?

177
00:09:55,529 --> 00:09:57,095
Those things are
flying off the lot.

178
00:09:57,129 --> 00:09:59,464
Frank, are you not
on board with this?

179
00:09:59,498 --> 00:10:01,232
I love what you're doing.

180
00:10:02,635 --> 00:10:05,303
I'm tired of rockets,
that's all.

181
00:10:05,337 --> 00:10:08,306
Could you give us a moment?
We'll continue this later.

182
00:10:12,344 --> 00:10:14,211
What is that, Shalimar?

183
00:10:17,749 --> 00:10:19,383
What's gotten into you?

184
00:10:19,417 --> 00:10:21,085
You're supposed to be
calming me down.

185
00:10:21,119 --> 00:10:23,220
Ted, I've got cancer.

186
00:10:23,254 --> 00:10:25,522
What?

187
00:10:25,557 --> 00:10:27,592
In my pancreas.

188
00:10:27,626 --> 00:10:29,225
I told Jim.
I thought he told you

189
00:10:29,259 --> 00:10:30,994
and you didn't want
to embarrass me.

190
00:10:35,265 --> 00:10:36,833
No.

191
00:10:36,867 --> 00:10:39,335
Maybe it's more of
a financial issue to him,

192
00:10:39,369 --> 00:10:41,571
but I'm glad he can
keep a secret.

193
00:10:42,740 --> 00:10:44,007
Financial?

194
00:10:44,041 --> 00:10:46,942
The minute I cash out,
I cash in.

195
00:10:46,977 --> 00:10:48,744
You two have to buy me out.

196
00:10:51,915 --> 00:10:53,983
You have cancer.

197
00:10:54,017 --> 00:10:56,151
See, if we still had Alfa,
I wouldn't have to worry

198
00:10:56,185 --> 00:10:58,353
about putting you
out of business.

199
00:11:00,289 --> 00:11:01,723
First of all,

200
00:11:01,757 --> 00:11:04,158
stop talking about money.

201
00:11:04,192 --> 00:11:06,027
Second, we are going
to get Chevy

202
00:11:06,061 --> 00:11:08,295
because you're going
to do your best work.

203
00:11:08,330 --> 00:11:10,364
Third, you're going
to build a wing

204
00:11:10,398 --> 00:11:12,867
at Sloan-Kettering
and beat this thing.

205
00:11:12,901 --> 00:11:15,703
Aye, aye.

206
00:11:24,178 --> 00:11:25,712
Will you tell Jim you told me?

207
00:11:25,747 --> 00:11:27,914
He'll see it on your face.

208
00:11:30,618 --> 00:11:32,985
Everybody loves astronauts.

209
00:11:34,354 --> 00:11:36,689
I've got to go lie down.

210
00:11:44,330 --> 00:11:45,965
Well, hello there.

211
00:11:45,999 --> 00:11:47,599
How are things in Glocca Morra?

212
00:11:47,634 --> 00:11:49,901
Hello. Can you hear me?

213
00:11:49,935 --> 00:11:52,570
I love it when you whisper like that.
What are you wearing?

214
00:11:52,604 --> 00:11:54,472
My uniform.

215
00:11:54,506 --> 00:11:57,175
I have one
and his flight's delayed.

216
00:11:57,209 --> 00:11:59,110
Who is he?
What's he do?

217
00:11:59,145 --> 00:12:00,779
I'm not sure,

218
00:12:00,813 --> 00:12:02,881
but he doesn't believe
my name's really Daisy.

219
00:12:02,915 --> 00:12:04,882
Use that.

220
00:12:14,425 --> 00:12:16,426
Shit.

221
00:12:21,531 --> 00:12:23,166
<i>Do you mind?</i>

222
00:12:24,835 --> 00:12:27,136
17, please.

223
00:12:31,575 --> 00:12:34,677
I'm sorry to bother you,
but we love your show.

224
00:12:34,712 --> 00:12:37,512
Oh, thank you.

225
00:12:41,617 --> 00:12:43,919
Can we get an autograph?

226
00:13:08,509 --> 00:13:10,543
I know you're not waving to me.

227
00:13:10,577 --> 00:13:12,812
Makes the delay
worthwhile, doesn't it?

228
00:13:12,847 --> 00:13:14,748
- Headed to Detroit?
- Eventually.

229
00:13:14,782 --> 00:13:16,415
Should we try LaGuardia?

230
00:13:16,450 --> 00:13:18,517
They already did.
Forget it.

231
00:13:20,020 --> 00:13:22,155
This is why I like
to drive everywhere.

232
00:13:22,189 --> 00:13:24,290
I'd live in my car if I could.

233
00:13:24,324 --> 00:13:26,725
You know, with her
in the backseat navigating.

234
00:13:26,760 --> 00:13:29,361
I'm Roger.

235
00:13:29,395 --> 00:13:31,029
- What's your name?
- Mikey.

236
00:13:31,064 --> 00:13:33,565
Well, Mikey, since we're
gonna be cell mates,

237
00:13:33,599 --> 00:13:35,500
I'm going to ask the screw
for a couple of drinks.

238
00:13:35,534 --> 00:13:37,335
Jim Beam.

239
00:13:37,370 --> 00:13:39,604
I'll make her bring them over.

240
00:13:39,639 --> 00:13:42,339
- Good idea.
- I'm full of 'em.

241
00:13:46,378 --> 00:13:47,979
I want a glass of water
with an onion

242
00:13:48,013 --> 00:13:49,747
and bring him
a double Jim Beam.

243
00:13:49,782 --> 00:13:51,849
And get me on that flight.

244
00:13:55,457 --> 00:13:56,998
_

245
00:13:58,825 --> 00:14:00,593
This is my day off.
We had plans.

246
00:14:00,694 --> 00:14:03,481
_

247
00:14:03,625 --> 00:14:05,836
_

248
00:14:06,399 --> 00:14:09,333
Well, you would rather spend the evening
laughing at Roger Sterling's jokes.

249
00:14:09,368 --> 00:14:12,970
I should return home.
I've overstayed my welcome.

250
00:14:13,253 --> 00:14:15,156
_

251
00:14:15,380 --> 00:14:16,512
_

252
00:14:17,517 --> 00:14:19,264
_

253
00:14:19,375 --> 00:14:21,093
_

254
00:14:22,414 --> 00:14:25,215
Well, I don't know
what's happened.

255
00:14:25,249 --> 00:14:27,250
I knew something was wrong.

256
00:14:27,285 --> 00:14:30,387
We have not had a fight.

257
00:14:31,389 --> 00:14:33,089
He's so far away

258
00:14:33,124 --> 00:14:35,325
that sometimes
when we're alone,

259
00:14:35,359 --> 00:14:37,928
I feel like
I'm making conversation.

